-- BHP, Cabcharge, Fortescue, Infigen, Rio, Westpac: Australian Stock Preview
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-07-06T22:45:51Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-06/bhp-cabcharge-fortesque-infigen-rio-westpac-australian-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed yesterday. All
prices are from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  
 The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in September
climbed 0.3 percent to 4,275 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank
of New York Australia ADR Index  rose 1.8 percent. The  S&P/ASX
200 Index  gained 1.3 percent to 4,276.10.  
 Mining shares: Copper futures for September climbed 1.9
percent to $2.971 a pound in New York.  
 BHP Billiton  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
rose 0.5 percent to A$37.15 in Sydney. Its American depositary
receipts climbed 1.8 percent in New York trading.  Rio Tinto
Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-largest mining company, lost
0.2 percent to A$65.10 in Sydney.  
 The spot price of iron ore delivered to China slumped to
its lowest level in almost five months as demand in the Asian
nation slows.  Fortescue Metals Groups Ltd.  (FMG AU), Australia’s
third-biggest iron-ore producer, advanced 3.2 percent to A$4.17.  
 Gold producers: Gold futures fell to a six-week low as
rallies in global stock markets eroded demand for the precious
metal as an alternative investment.  Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM
AU), Australia’s biggest gold producer, slipped 0.5 percent to
A$34.16.  
 Financial companies: Australian banks will need to borrow
at least A$130 billion ($111 billion) during the next year to
repay existing debts and fund mortgage growth, the Australia
Financial Review reported, citing figures from JPMorgan Chase &
Co.       Commonwealth Bank of Australia  (CBA AU), the nation’s
biggest lender by market value, climbed 2.3 percent to A$48.89.
 Westpac Banking Corp.  (WBC AU), the second largest, rose 3
percent A$21.41.  
 Cabcharge Australia Ltd.  (CAB AU): The operator of
Australia’s largest taxi payment system was downgraded to
“hold” from “buy” at Deutsche Bank AG by equity analyst  Tim Plumbe . Cabcharge gained 1.4 percent to A$5.04.  
 Infigen Energy  (IFN AU): The Australian wind-energy project
developer was raised to “neutral” from “underperform” at
Credit Suisse Group AG. Infigen shares climbed 3.2 percent to 80
Australian cents.  
 Western Areas NL  (WSA AU): Western Areas, a nickel supplier
to BHP Billiton, was raised to “buy” from “neutral” at UBS
AG by equity analyst  Jonathan Battershill . Western Areas was
unchanged at A$3.82.  
